04636nam a22006975i 9780271035079DE-B159720210526051534.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210526t20212008pau    fo  d z      eng d  a97802710350797 a10.1515/97802710350792doi  a(DE-B1597)583683  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  apaucUS-PA 7aPOL0030002bisacsh04a362.9732231 aDzur, Albert W., eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aDemocratic Professionalism :bCitizen Participation and the Reconstruction of Professional Ethics, Identity, and Practice /cAlbert W. Dzur. 1aUniversity Park, PA : bPenn State University Press, c[2021] 4cÂ©2008  a1 online resource (288 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFrontmatter -- tCONTENTS -- tAcknowledgments -- tIntroduction: The Ethics and Politics of Professions -- t1 The Missing Agents of Contemporary Democratic Thought -- t2 Beyond Self-Interest: The Apolitical Picture of Professionals -- t3 Professionals versus Democracy: The Radical Critique of Technocrats, Disabling Experts, and Task Monopolists -- t4 Task Sharing for Democracy: Themes from Political Theory -- t5 Public Journalism -- t6 Restorative Justice -- t7 Bioethics -- t8 Context and Consequences: The Duties of Democratic Professionals -- tConclusion: The University's Role in the Democratization of Professional Ethics -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aBringing expert knowledge to bear in an open and deliberative way to help solve pressing social problems is a major concern today, when technocratic and bureaucratic decision making often occurs with little or no input from the general public. Albert Dzur proposes an approach he calls "democratic professionalism" to build bridges between specialists in domains like law, medicine, and journalism and the lay public in such a way as to enable and enhance broader public engagement with and deliberation about major social issues. Sparking a critical and constructive dialogue among social theories of the professions, professional ethics, and political theories of deliberative democracy, Dzur reveals interests, motivations, strengths, and vulnerabilities in conventional professional roles that provide guideposts for this new approach. He then applies it in examining three practical arenas in which experiments in collaboration and power-sharing between professionals and citizens have been undertaken: public journalism, restorative justice, and the bioethics movement. Finally, he draws lessons from these cases to refine this innovative theory and identify the kinds of challenges practitioners face in being both democratic and professional.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 26. Mai 2021) 0aPolitical participationxMoral and ethical aspectsxUnited States. 0aPolitical participationxMoral and ethical aspectszUnited States. 0aProfessional employeesxPolitical activityxUnited States. 0aProfessional employeesxPolitical activityzUnited States. 0aProfessional ethicsxUnited States. 0aProfessional ethicszUnited States. 0aSocial advocacyxUnited States. 0aSocial advocacyzUnited States. 7aPOLITICAL SCIENCE / Civics & Citizenship.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertPenn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014z978311074526940uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780271035079423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780271035079.jpg  a978-3-11-074526-9  Penn State University Press Complete eBook-Package Pre-2014b2014  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_SN  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_SN  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK